Kurt Julian Weill (pronounced /waɪl/; German: [vaɪl]; March 2, 1900 – April 3, 1950) was a German-born American composer, a figure whose career spanned continents and genres, leaving an indelible mark on both the concert hall and the theatrical stage. His early years in Germany saw him rise to prominence as a leading composer for the stage, particularly recognized for his groundbreaking collaborations with the playwright [Bertolt Brecht](/Bertolt_Brecht). Their partnership produced some of Weill's most iconic works, including the seminal [The Threepenny Opera](/The_Threepenny_Opera), a biting satire that introduced the world to the enduringly popular ballad "[Mack the Knife](/Mack_the_Knife)". Weill harbored a profound belief in the social utility of music, a concept he championed through his embrace of [Gebrauchsmusik](/Gebrauchsmusik) – music intended for practical, functional purposes. Beyond his theatrical triumphs, he also composed significant works for the concert hall and explored themes of [Jewish](/Jewish) identity in several of his compositions. The rise of the [Nazi](/Nazi) regime in Germany forced Weill to flee his homeland in 1933, leading him to immigrate to the United States two years later. In his adopted country, he continued to shape American musical theater with acclaimed works such as [Lady in the Dark](/Lady_in_the_Dark) and the opera [Street Scene](/Street_Scene_(opera)).

## Family and Childhood

Born on March 2, 1900, Kurt Weill was the third of four children born to Albert Weill (1867–1950) and Emma Weill (née Ackermann; 1872–1955). He was raised in a devout [Jewish](/Jewish) household in Dessau, located in [Saxony](/Province_of_Saxony). His father, Albert, served as a [cantor](/Hazzan) in their community. Weill's musical journey began at the tender age of twelve when he started taking piano lessons. It was around this time that he first ventured into composing, with his earliest known musical composition, "Mi Addir: Jewish Wedding Song," dating back to 1913.

His formal musical education continued in 1915 under the tutelage of Albert Bing, the [kapellmeister](/Kapellmeister) at the Herzogliches Hoftheater zu Dessau. Bing provided Weill with comprehensive instruction in piano, composition, music theory, and conducting. Weill made his public debut as a pianist in 1915, performing as both a soloist and an accompanist. In the subsequent years, he dedicated himself to composing numerous [lieder](/Lieder), setting to music the words of prominent poets including [Joseph von Eichendorff](/Joseph_Freiherr_von_Eichendorff), [Arno Holz](/Arno_Holz), and [Anna Ritter](/Anna_Ritter). He also penned a cycle of five songs titled *Ofrahs Lieder*, drawing from a German translation of a text by [Yehuda Halevi](/Yehuda_Halevi).

In 1918, Weill achieved his [Abitur](/Abitur), the German university entrance qualification, from the Oberrealschule in Dessau. At the age of eighteen, he enrolled at the [Berliner Hochschule für Musik](/Berlin_University_of_the_Arts), where he pursued composition studies with [Engelbert Humperdinck](/Engelbert_Humperdinck_(composer)). His education extended to [conducting](/Conducting) under [Rudolf Krasselt], and [counterpoint](/Counterpoint) with Friedrich E. Koch. Concurrently, he attended lectures on philosophy delivered by luminaries such as [Max Dessoir](/Max_Dessoir) and [Ernst Cassirer](/Ernst_Cassirer). That same year, he composed his first [string quartet](/String_quartet), a work in B minor.

## Musical Career

### Early Work and Compositions

The economic repercussions of [World War I](/World_War_I) cast a long shadow over Weill's family, leading to financial difficulties. In July 1919, he temporarily suspended his studies and returned to Dessau. There, he secured a position as a [répétiteur](/R%C3%A9p%C3%A9titeur) at the Friedrich-Theater, working under the new [Kapellmeister](/Kapellmeister), [Hans Knappertsbusch](/Hans_Knappertsbusch). During this period, his compositional output included an [orchestral suite](/Orchestral_suite) in E-flat major, a [symphonic poem](/Symphonic_poem) inspired by [Rainer Maria Rilke](/Rainer_Maria_Rilke)'s *The Lay of the Love and Death of Cornet Christopher Rilke*, and *Schilflieder* ("Reed Songs"), a [cycle](/Song_cycle) of five songs based on poems by [Nikolaus Lenau](/Nikolaus_Lenau).

In December 1919, Weill was appointed Kapellmeister at the newly established Stadttheater in [Lüdenscheid](/L%C3%BCdenscheid), a position facilitated by his former teacher, Humperdinck. For five months, he was responsible for directing opera, operetta, and [singspiel](/Singspiel). His compositions from this time include a [cello sonata](/Cello_sonata) and *Ninon de Lenclos*, a now-lost [one-act](/One-act) operatic adaptation of a 1905 play by [Ernst Hardt](/Ernst_Hardt). From May to September 1920, Weill spent time in [Leipzig](/Leipzig), where his father had taken on the directorship of a Jewish orphanage located on [Gottschedstrasse](/Gottschedstrasse_(Leipzig)). Before returning to Berlin in September 1920, he composed *Sulamith*, a choral fantasy intended for soprano, female choir, and orchestra.

### Studies with Busoni

Upon his return to Berlin, Weill sought an audience with the esteemed composer [Ferruccio Busoni](/Ferruccio_Busoni) in December 1920. Impressed by Weill's compositions, Busoni accepted him into his master class at the [Preussische Akademie der Künste](/Akademie_der_K%C3%BCnste) in Berlin, where he was one of five selected students.

From January 1921 to December 1923, Weill studied composition with Busoni and also took counterpoint lessons with [Philipp Jarnach](/Philipp_Jarnach). His early works during this period included his first [symphony](/Symphony), *Sinfonie in einem Satz*, along with the lieder *Die Bekehrte* (setting a text by [Johann Wolfgang von Goethe](/Johann_Wolfgang_von_Goethe)) and two *Rilkelieder* for voice and piano. Busoni, nearing the end of his life, exerted a profound influence on Weill. While Weill's initial compositions bore the hallmarks of the post-[Wagnerian](/Richard_Wagner) [Romanticism](/Romanticism) and [Expressionism](/Expressionism) prevalent in German classical music, Busoni championed [Neoclassicism](/Neoclassicism). This influence became particularly evident in Weill's vocal and stage works, which gradually shifted from direct emotional representation to a more detached, often ironic, commentary. This stylistic evolution aligned with Weill's own developing ideas about [Epic theater](/Epic_theater) and the [Verfremdungseffekt](/Distancing_effect) (distancing effect), concepts later espoused by his future collaborator, Brecht.

To supplement his family's income in Leipzig, Weill also worked as a pianist in a Bierkeller tavern. In 1922, he became involved with the [November Group](/November_Group_(German)), a collective of [leftist](/Leftist) Berlin artists that included composers like [Hanns Eisler](/Hanns_Eisler) and [Stefan Wolpe](/Stefan_Wolpe). That same year, he composed a psalm, a [divertimento](/Divertimento) for orchestra, and *Sinfonia Sacra: Fantasia, Passacaglia, and Hymnus* for Orchestra. On November 18, 1922, his children's [pantomime](/Pantomime), *Die Zaubernacht* (*The Magic Night*), premiered at the Theater am Kurfürstendamm, marking the first public performance of any of Weill's works in the realm of musical theatre.

Driven by financial necessity, Weill took on private students for music theory and composition between 1923 and 1925. Among his pupils were the renowned pianist [Claudio Arrau](/Claudio_Arrau), conductor [Maurice Abravanel](/Maurice_Abravanel), [Heinz Jolles (later known as Henry Jolles)](/Henry_Jolles), composer [Nikos Skalkottas](/Nikos_Skalkottas), and singer [Esther Zweig](/Esther_Zweig). Arrau, Abravanel, and Jolles remained close friends of Weill thereafter. Notably, Jolles's only surviving composition predating the rise of the [Nazi](/Nazi) regime in 1933 is a fragment of a four-piano work he and Weill created together.

Weill's compositions during his final year of study included *Quodlibet*, an orchestral suite derived from *Die Zaubernacht*; *Frauentanz*, a collection of seven medieval poems for soprano and a chamber ensemble; and *Recordare*, a choral work for soprano and children's choir, setting text from the [Book of Lamentations](/Book_of_Lamentations). Further premieres that year included a performance of his *Divertimento for Orchestra* by the [Berlin Philharmonic](/Berlin_Philharmonic) under the baton of [Heinz Unger](/Heinz_Unger) on April 10, 1923. The [Hindemith-Amar Quartet](/Amar_Quartet) presented Weill's *String Quartet*, Op. 8, on June 24, 1923. Weill completed his studies with Busoni in December 1923.

### Success in the 1920s and Early 1930s

In 1922, Weill became affiliated with the Novembergruppe, a significant association of [leftist](/Leftist) Berlin artists. This period saw him forge a crucial creative partnership with the dramatist [Georg Kaiser](/Georg_Kaiser), whom he met in February 1924 through conductor [Fritz Busch](/Fritz_Busch). Their collaboration resulted in several influential one-act operas. It was at Kaiser's home in [Grünheide](/Gr%C3%BCnheide) during the summer of 1924 that Weill first encountered the singer and actress [Lotte Lenya](/Lotte_Lenya). Their tempestuous relationship led to two marriages, first in 1926 and again in 1937, following a divorce in 1933. Lenya became a steadfast supporter of Weill's work and, after his death, dedicated herself to promoting his music, ultimately establishing the Kurt Weill Foundation. From November 1924 to May 1929, Weill contributed hundreds of reviews to *Der deutsche Rundfunk*, an influential radio program guide. Hans Siebert von Heister, who had previously worked with Weill in the November Group, offered him this position shortly after becoming editor-in-chief.

Following their 1926 marriage, Weill and Lenya resided for a period in Georg Kaiser's apartment in Berlin-Charlottenburg, while Kaiser preferred his lakeside residence.

While Weill achieved some recognition for his early mature non-stage works, such as the *String Quartet*, Op. 8, and the *Concerto for Violin and Wind Orchestra*, Op. 12—pieces that showed the influence of composers like [Gustav Mahler](/Gustav_Mahler), [Arnold Schoenberg](/Arnold_Schoenberg), and [Igor Stravinsky](/Igor_Stravinsky)—he increasingly gravitated towards vocal music and the realm of musical theatre. His stage works and songs garnered considerable popularity in Germany during the late 1920s and early 1930s. Weill's music earned admiration from esteemed composers including [Alban Berg](/Alban_Berg), [Alexander von Zemlinsky](/Alexander_von_Zemlinsky), [Darius Milhaud](/Darius_Milhaud), and Stravinsky. However, it also faced criticism from figures like Schoenberg, who later revised his opinion, and [Anton Webern](/Anton_Webern).

His most celebrated composition remains [The Threepenny Opera](/The_Threepenny_Opera) (1928), a bold reimagining of John Gay's [The Beggar's Opera](/The_Beggar%27s_Opera), created in collaboration with [Bertolt Brecht](/Bertolt_Brecht). The original production of *The Threepenny Opera* in 1928 was directed by Erich Engel. The work features Weill's most famous song, "[Mack the Knife](/Mack_the_Knife)" (originally titled "Die Moritat von Mackie Messer"). Textually, *Threepenny Opera*, much like its predecessor, served as a vehicle for satire and social commentary. For Weill, however, it represented more than just a lyrical critique; it was an opportunity to "make opera the subject matter for an evening in the theater," a step in his lifelong endeavor to "reform" opera for the contemporary stage. The successful stage production was subsequently adapted into a film by [G. W. Pabst](/G._W._Pabst) in two language versions: *Die 3-Groschen-Oper* and *L'opéra de quat' sous*. Weill and Brecht attempted to halt the film adaptation through a highly publicized lawsuit, which Weill ultimately won, while Brecht lost.

Weill continued his fruitful collaboration with Brecht on the musical *Happy End* (1929), which includes the well-known songs "Surabaya Johnny," "Bilbao Song," and "Sailor's Tango." They also collaborated on the children's opera *Der Jasager* (1930) and the opera *Rise and Fall of the City of Mahagonny* (1930), the latter featuring the iconic "[Alabama Song](/Alabama_Song)," later famously covered by [The Doors](/The_Doors), among many others. Weill's creative partnership with Brecht, though artistically successful, dissolved in 1930 due to political disagreements. While Weill held socialist sympathies, Brecht's increasingly radical left-wing agenda proved irreconcilable. Weill, as recounted by his wife Lotte Lenya, stated he was unable to "set the [Communist Manifesto](/Communist_Manifesto) to music."

During his time in Germany in the early 1930s, Weill also worked with the American virtuoso banjoist [Mike Danzi](/Mike_Danzi) on an early production of his opera *Rise and Fall of the City of Mahagonny*. Weill reportedly commended Danzi's accurate interpretation of the score's chords, noting that many other banjoists had complained the parts were not written for their instrument.

## Life in Paris and New York

The escalating persecution of Jewish artists and intellectuals under the [Nazi](/Nazi) regime compelled Kurt Weill to flee [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany) in March 1933. As a prominent Jewish composer with expressed political views, Weill was officially denounced and targeted by the Nazi authorities, who actively interfered with performances of his more recent stage works, including *Rise and Fall of the City of Mahagonny* (*Aufstieg und Fall der Stadt Mahagonny*, 1930), *Die Bürgschaft* (1932), and *Der Silbersee* (1933). Facing an untenable situation in his homeland, he initially sought refuge in Paris. There, he once again collaborated with Brecht on the ballet-chanté [The Seven Deadly Sins](/The_Seven_Deadly_Sins_(ballet_chant%C3%A9)), following a proposed project with [Jean Cocteau](/Jean_Cocteau) that ultimately failed to materialize.

On April 13, 1933, Weill's musical *The Threepenny Opera* premiered on Broadway. Despite a promising start, the production closed after only 13 performances amidst mixed reviews. In 1934, he completed his Symphony No. 2, which would be his final purely orchestral work. This symphony was conducted in both Amsterdam and New York by the renowned [Bruno Walter](/Bruno_Walter). That same year, he also composed the music for [Jacques Deval](/Jacques_Deval)'s play *Marie Galante* [fr]. A production of his operetta *Der Kuhhandel* (*A Kingdom for a Cow*) brought him to London in 1935. Later that year, he traveled to the United States in connection with *The Eternal Road* [8], a "Biblical Drama" by [Franz Werfel](/Franz_Werfel). Commissioned by members of New York's Jewish community, the play premiered in 1937 at the [Manhattan Opera House](/Manhattan_Opera_House) and enjoyed a successful run of 153 performances.

Weill and his wife, Lotte Lenya, relocated to New York City on September 10, 1935. They initially resided at the St. Moritz Hotel before moving to an apartment on East 62nd Street. During the summer of 1936, they rented an old house near [Pine Brook Country Club](/Pine_Brook_Country_Club) in [Nichols, Connecticut](/Nichols,_Connecticut). This location served as the summer home for the [Group Theatre](/Group_Theatre_(New_York)), and it was here that Weill, alongside playwright [Paul Green](/Paul_Green_(playwright)), worked on completing *Johnny Johnson*. Among the other notable artists who spent that summer at Pine Brook were [Elia Kazan](/Elia_Kazan), [Harry Morgan](/Harry_Morgan), [John Garfield](/John_Garfield), [Lee J. Cobb](/Lee_J._Cobb), [Will Geer](/Will_Geer), [Clifford Odets](/Clifford_Odets), [Howard da Silva](/Howard_da_Silva), and [Irwin Shaw](/Irwin_Shaw).

Rather than attempting to replicate the musical style of his European compositions, Weill dedicated himself to studying American popular music and stage traditions. His American output featured individual songs and complete shows that not only garnered significant respect and admiration but are also considered pivotal in the evolution of the American [musical](/Musical_theatre). In 1939, he composed the score for *Railroads on Parade*, a grand musical spectacle presented at the [1939 World's Fair](/1939_World%27s_Fair) in New York to celebrate the American railroad industry, with a book by Edward Hungerford. Uniquely among Broadway composers of his time, Weill insisted on orchestrating his own works, with very few exceptions, such as the dance music in *Street Scene*. He collaborated with notable writers, including [Maxwell Anderson](/Maxwell_Anderson) and [Ira Gershwin](/Ira_Gershwin), and also penned a film score for director [Fritz Lang](/Fritz_Lang) in *You and Me* (1938). Weill was driven by the ambition to forge a new path for American opera, one that would achieve both commercial success and artistic merit. His most significant endeavor in this pursuit was *Street Scene*, based on a play by [Elmer Rice](/Elmer_Rice) with lyrics by [Langston Hughes](/Langston_Hughes). For his contribution to *Street Scene*, Weill was honored with the inaugural [Tony Award](/Tony_Award) for [Best Original Score](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Original_Score).

During the 1940s, Weill resided in [downstate New York](/Downstate_New_York), near the [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) border, making frequent trips to both New York City and Hollywood for his theatrical and cinematic projects. Weill actively supported political movements advocating for American involvement in [World War II](/World_War_II). Once America entered the war in 1941, he enthusiastically participated in numerous artistic initiatives aimed at bolstering the war effort, both overseas and on the [home front](/Home_front). He and Maxwell Anderson also joined the civil defense effort, serving as air raid wardens on [High Tor Mountain](/High_Tor_State_Park) between their homes in [New City, New York](/New_City,_New_York) and [Haverstraw, New York](/Haverstraw_(village),_New_York) in [Rockland County](/Rockland_County,_New_York). Kurt Weill officially became a [naturalized citizen](/Naturalized_citizen) of the United States on August 27, 1943.

Weill consistently held the ideal of creating music with a socially beneficial purpose. In the United States, he composed *Down in the Valley*, an opera that incorporated the folk song of the same name and other American folk melodies. He also wrote several songs to support the American war effort, including the satirical "Schickelgruber" (with lyrics by [Howard Dietz](/Howard_Dietz)), "Buddy on the Nightshift" (with [Oscar Hammerstein](/Oscar_Hammerstein_II)), and—reuniting with Brecht—the ["Ballad of the Nazi Soldier's Wife" ("Und was bekam des Soldaten Weib?").](/Und_was_bekam_des_Soldaten_Weib%3F) This latter song, intended for broadcast to Germany, depicted the progression of the Nazi war machine through the gifts sent by a soldier at the front to his proud wife at home: initially furs from Oslo, then a silk dress from Paris, and finally, a widow's veil from Russia.

Beyond the widely recognized "[Mack the Knife](/Mack_the_Knife)" and "[Pirate Jenny](/Pirate_Jenny)" from *The Threepenny Opera*, his most enduringly popular songs include "[Alabama Song](/Alabama_Song)" (from *Mahagonny*), "Surabaya Johnny" (from *Happy End*), "[Speak Low](/Speak_Low)" (from [One Touch of Venus](/One_Touch_of_Venus)), "Lost in the Stars" (from the musical of the same name), "[My Ship](/My_Ship)" (from [Lady in the Dark](/Lady_in_the_Dark)), and "[September Song](/September_Song)" (from [Knickerbocker Holiday](/Knickerbocker_Holiday)).

## Death

Kurt Weill experienced a heart attack shortly after celebrating his 50th birthday and passed away on April 3, 1950, in New York City. He was laid to rest in Mount Repose Cemetery in [Haverstraw, New York](/Haverstraw,_New_York). The inscription on his gravestone features lyrics from the song "A Bird of Passage" from *Lost in the Stars*, a poignant adaptation of a quotation from the [Venerable Bede](/Venerable_Bede):

This is the life of men on earth:

Out of darkness we come at birth

Into a lamplit room, and then –

Go forward into dark again.

(lyric: [Maxwell Anderson](/Maxwell_Anderson))

An excerpt from [Maxwell Anderson](/Maxwell_Anderson)'s eulogy for Weill eloquently captured the composer's legacy:

I wish, of course, that he had been lucky enough to have had a little more time for his work. I could wish the times in which he lived had been less troubled. But these things were as they were – and Kurt managed to make thousands of beautiful things during the short and troubled time he had ...

## Influence

Weill's music continues to resonate across both [popular](/Popular_music) and [classical](/Classical_music) arenas. During his lifetime, his work was most famously interpreted by his wife, [Lotte Lenya](/Lotte_Lenya). However, in the years following his death, "[Mack the Knife](/Mack_the_Knife)" gained widespread recognition as a jazz standard, notably through recordings by [Louis Armstrong](/Louis_Armstrong) and [Bobby Darin](/Bobby_Darin). Since then, his music has been recorded by an eclectic array of performers, spanning genres and generations, including [Nina Simone](/Nina_Simone), [Judy Garland](/Judy_Garland), [Frank Sinatra](/Frank_Sinatra), [The Doors](/The_Doors), [Ella Fitzgerald](/Ella_Fitzgerald), [David Bowie](/David_Bowie), [Robbie Williams](/Robbie_Williams), [Judy Collins](/Judy_Collins), [John Zorn](/John_Zorn), [Dagmar Krause](/Dagmar_Krause), [Steeleye Span](/Steeleye_Span), [The Young Gods](/The_Young_Gods), and [PJ Harvey](/PJ_Harvey). His compositions have also been performed by prestigious institutions such as the [Metropolitan Opera](/Metropolitan_Opera) and the [Vienna Radio Symphony Orchestra](/Vienna_Radio_Symphony_Orchestra). Vocalists as diverse as [Teresa Stratas](/Teresa_Stratas), [Ute Lemper](/Ute_Lemper), [Gisela May](/Gisela_May), [Anne Sofie von Otter](/Anne_Sofie_von_Otter), [Max Raabe](/Max_Raabe), [Heinz Karl Gruber](/Heinz_Karl_Gruber), [Dee Dee Bridgewater](/Dee_Dee_Bridgewater), and [Marianne Faithfull](/Marianne_Faithfull) have dedicated entire albums to his music.

In 1985, producer [Hal Willner](/Hal_Willner) released *Lost in the Stars: The Music of Kurt Weill*, a [tribute album](/Tribute_album) featuring interpretations of Weill's songs by a diverse group of artists, including [Todd Rundgren](/Todd_Rundgren), [Tom Waits](/Tom_Waits), [Lou Reed](/Lou_Reed), [Charlie Haden](/Charlie_Haden), and [Sting](/Sting_(musician)).

[Amanda Palmer](/Amanda_Palmer), the singer-pianist of the Brechtian Punk Cabaret duo [The Dresden Dolls](/The_Dresden_Dolls), has Kurt Weill's name displayed on her keyboard as a tribute. In 1991, the influential [Swiss](/Switzerland) [industrial](/Industrial_music) band [The Young Gods](/The_Young_Gods) released *The Young Gods Play Kurt Weill*, an album dedicated to their interpretations of his songs. Weill's work has also been cited as a significant influence on [Goldfrapp](/Goldfrapp)'s album *Felt Mountain*. In 2008, Canadian musicians, including [Sarah Slean](/Sarah_Slean) and [Mary Margaret O'Hara](/Mary_Margaret_O%27Hara), performed Weill's songs in a tribute concert during the inaugural Canwest Cabaret Festival in Toronto. In 2009, [Duke Special](/Duke_Special) released an EP, *Huckleberry Finn*, featuring five songs from an unfinished musical by Kurt Weill based on [Mark Twain](/Mark_Twain)'s novel [Adventures of Huckleberry Finn](/Adventures_of_Huckleberry_Finn).

Kurt Weill is recognized as a member of the [American Theater Hall of Fame](/American_Theater_Hall_of_Fame).

## Kurt Weill Centre

The Kurt Weill Centre (German: Kurt-Weill-Zentrum) was established in Dessau in 1993. It functions as a museum, library, archive, and media center, and hosts an annual festival dedicated to celebrating the composer's oeuvre. The center is housed in the Feininger house, a structure designed by architect [Walter Gropius](/Walter_Gropius) and formerly inhabited by the artist [Lyonel Feininger](/Lyonel_Feininger). This property is part of the UNESCO World Heritage site, the [Bauhaus and its Sites in Weimar, Dessau and Bernau](/Bauhaus_and_its_Sites_in_Weimar,_Dessau_and_Bernau). The Kurt Weill Centre, with its extensive collection of materials pertaining to the composer, is designated as a cultural memorial of national importance. It is also recognized as one of the "Beacons of light" by the [Konferenz Nationaler Kultureinrichtungen](/Konferenz_Nationaler_Kultureinrichtungen) (Conference of National Cultural Institutions), an organization representing cultural institutions in the [new states of Germany](/New_states_of_Germany), formerly [East Germany](/East_Germany).

## Kurt Weill Foundation for Music

Founded in 1962 by [Lotte Lenya](/Lotte_Lenya), the Kurt Weill Foundation for Music is a non-profit, private organization dedicated to fostering an understanding of Weill's life and works and to preserving the legacies of both Weill and Lenya. The foundation oversees the internationally acclaimed Lotte Lenya Competition, manages grant programs, sponsorships, and fellowships, operates the Weill-Lenya Research Center, and awards the Kurt Weill Prize. It also publishes the comprehensive Kurt Weill Edition and the Kurt Weill Newsletter. The board of trustees of this New York-based organization has included prominent figures such as [Harold Prince](/Harold_Prince), [Victoria Clark](/Victoria_Clark), [Jeanine Tesori](/Jeanine_Tesori), [Tazewell Thompson](/Tazewell_Thompson), and [Teresa Stratas](/Teresa_Stratas).

## Relatives

Weill's maternal grandmother was Jeanette Hochstetter of Liedolsheim in [Baden-Württemberg](/Baden-W%C3%BCrttemberg). Weill belonged to the Hochstetter family, which produced four notable individuals who achieved distinction in music and literature. His first cousin once removed, [Caesar Hochstetter](/Caesar_Hochstetter) (born January 12, 1863, in [Ladenburg](/Ladenburg), a suburb of [Mannheim](/Mannheim) – his date and place of death are unknown but likely occurred during [The Holocaust](/The_Holocaust)), was a composer and arranger who collaborated with [Max Reger](/Max_Reger). Caesar dedicated his *Aquarelles*, Op. 25, to Kurt.

Caesar's younger brother, Gustav Hochstetter [de] (born May 12, 1873, in [Mannheim](/Mannheim) – died 1942 in [Theresienstadt concentration camp](/Theresienstadt_concentration_camp)), was a Professor of Literature at the University of Brussels, a writer, and a poet, and was a friend of [Wilhelm Busch](/Wilhelm_Busch). Weill's second cousin was the child prodigy pianist [Lisy Fischer](/Lisy_Fischer) (born August 22, 1900, in Zürich, Switzerland – died June 6, 1999, in [Newcastle upon Tyne](/Newcastle_upon_Tyne), England).

